qas.question: Who was the adversary of Zeus in the titanomachy?
Who did the narrator confuse with Phyton?
Who was represented as a dragon?

context: The earth deity had power over the ghostly world, and it is believed that she was the deity behind the oracle. The older tales mentioned two dragons who were perhaps intentionally conflated. A female dragon named Delphyne (δελφύς, "womb"), who is obviously connected with Delphi and Apollo Delphinios, and a male serpent <a0_0><a1_0>Typhon<a1_0/><a0_0/> (τύφειν, "to smoke"), the adversary of Zeus in the Titanomachy, who the narrators confused with Python. <a2_0>Python<a2_0/> was the good daemon (ἀγαθὸς δαίμων) of the temple as it appears in Minoan religion, but she was represented as a dragon, as often happens in Northern European folklore as well as in the East.
